        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-06-17T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-06-17T19:00:00-05:00" n="894"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d894">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.248/576: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-06-17T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 17, 1942—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>282. Your no. 607, June 15, 7 p.m. General Arnold, Chief, United States Air
                    Corps, requests cautious procedure in connection with any negotiations looking
                    towards presentation of planes to Turkey. First and foremost, War Department
                    desires to obtain permission for secret instruments to be removed from planes
                    and for the personnel to leave Turkey without parole. These would be cardinal
                    points of any agreement to transfer planes to Turkey.</p>
                <p>The Department will be glad to discuss with General Arnold any suggestions
                    regarding the planes which you may receive from the Turkish authorities. As
                    regards the personnel, the Department realizes that some time might elapse
                    before the men could all be conveniently released. An assurance now by the
                    Turkish Government as to its ultimate intentions might be considered
                    satisfactory on this point.</p>
                <p>Please reply as soon as possible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
